				\begin{document}$$ Log(N)= \log \left({N}_0\right)-{\left(\frac{t}{\delta}\right)}^n $$\end{document}LogN=logN0−tδnwhere N is the surviving virus titer after treatment, N
0 is the initial virus titer, δ is the time (min or days) of first logarithm decline in virus titer, and n is the shape parameter. The n value provides an indication of the shape of the response curve. If n > 1, the curve is convex (it forms a shoulder-shaped response), if n < 1, the curve is concave (it forms a tail-shaped response), and if n = 1, the curve is a straight line and can be described by a linear model.

